orax'' sp.<nowiki>'</nowiki> and <nowiki>'</nowiki>''Paratypothorax''-Like Forms<nowiki>'</nowiki>," Irmis (2005) p. 78</ref> | * Arizona<ref name="irmis2005-78-Paratypothorax-other" /> | * Sonsela<ref name="irmis2005-78-Paratypothorax-other" /> | | |- | rowspan="2" | ''[[Calyptosuchus]]''<ref name="irmis2005-77-stagonolepis">"Vertebrate Fauna; Stagonolepididae," Irmis (2005) p. 77</ref> | ''C. wellesi''<ref name="irmis2005-77-stagonolepis-wellesi">"Vertebrate Fauna; Stagonolepididae; ''Stagonolepis wellesi''," Irmis (2005) p. 77</ref> | * Arizona<ref name="irmis2005-77-stagonolepis-wellesi" /> | * Sonsela<ref name="irmis2005-77-stagonolepis-wellesi" /> * Blue Mesa<ref name="irmis2005-77-stagonolepis-wellesi" /> * Mesa Redondo<ref name="irmis2005-77-stagonolepis-wellesi" /> | Common in the lower strata of the Chinle Formation, although "[n]on-armor material is comparatively rare".<ref name="irmis2005-77-stagonolepis-wellesi" /> | |- | Indeterminate<ref name="irmis2005-77-stagonolepis-sp">"Vertebrate Fauna; Stagonolepididae; ''Stagonolepis'' sp." Irmis (2005) p. 77</ref> | * Arizona<ref name="irmis2005-77-stagonolepis-sp" /> | * Sonsela<ref name="irmis2005-77-stagonolepis-sp" /> | | A partial skeleton from Petrified Forest National Park is not only the uppermost occurrence of ''Stagonolepis'' in the park, but may represent a new species as well.<ref name="irmis2005-77-stagonolepis-sp" /> |- |''[[Scutarx]]''<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=Parker|first=William G.|date=2016-01-21|title=Revised phylogenetic analysis of the Aetosauria (Archosauria: Pseudosuchia); assessing the effects of incongruent morphological character sets|journal=PeerJ|volume=4|doi=10.7717/peerj.1583|issn=2167-8359|pmc=4727975|pmid=26819845}}</ref> |''S. deltatylus''<ref name=":0" /> | * Arizona<ref name=":0" /> | * Sonsela<ref name=":0" /> | | |- |''[[Stenomyti]]'' |''S. huangae'' | * Colorado | * "Red siltstone" | | |- | ''[[Typothorax]]''<ref name="irmis2005-7778-Typothorax">"Vertebrate Fauna; Stagonolepididae; ''Typothorax coccinarum''," Irmis (2005) pp. 77-78</ref> | ''T. coccinarum''<ref name="irmis2005-7778-Typothorax" /> | * Arizona<ref name="irmis2005-7778-Typothorax" /> | * Owl Rock<ref name="irmis2005-7778-Typothorax" /> * Petrified Forest<ref name="irmis2005-7778-Typothorax" /> * Sonsela<ref name="irmis2005-7778-Typothorax" /> | Common in the Owl Rock and Petrified Forest Members.<ref name="irmis2005-7778-Typothorax" /> | Almost all of the known Chinlean ''Typothorax'' fossils are isolated whole or fragmentary osteoderms.<ref name="irmis2005-7778-Typothorax" /> |- |}
